695500992">How do I find the volume of a cone with the slant height?</a></l=
i></ul></section></div></div></section><div class=3D"jsx-3880559791 spacerB=
ottom"></div><div id=3D"calculator-description" class=3D"jsx-3880559791"><d=
iv class=3D"StyledHtml jsx-2924063361 jsx-314497600"><div class=3D"contentP=
art css-12zi0x1"><div class=3D"textBlock"><p>Calculate the volume of any co=
ne, from traffic cones to ice creams, from funnels to the roofs of castles,=
 with our calculator! Follow us on a quick journey around these round solid=
s.</p>
<p>Here you will learn:</p>
<ul>
<li>What is a cone;</li>
<li>But most importantly, what is a <strong>frustum</strong>;</li>
<li>How to find the volume of a cone;</li>
<li>How to calculate the volume of a frustum;</li>
<li>How to calculate the volume of a cone with its slant height;</li>
<li>Some examples; and</li>
<li>A couple of words about rockets.</li>
</ul>
<p>Learning about cones will be as smooth as them, but what about more "edg=
y" shapes? Head to our <a href=3D"https://www.calctool.org/math-and-statist=
ics/pyramid-volume" class=3D"js-link">pyramid volume calculator</a> to know=
 the answer!</p>
</div></div><div class=3D"jsx-1030690091 contentPartPromo"><div><div id=3D"=
/52555387/omnicalculator.com_300x250_1" style=3D"min-height: 250px; max-hei=
ght: 250px;"></div></div></div><div class=3D"contentPart css-12zi0x1"><h2 i=
d=3D"what-is-a-cone">What is a cone?</h2>
<div class=3D"textBlock"><p>A cone is a <strong>solid of revolution</strong=
>, a three-dimensional shape obtained by a complete rotation of a polygon a=
round a main axis. The other principal solids of revolutions are:</p>
<ul>
<li>The sphere;</li>
<li>The cylinder; and</li>
<li>The truncated cone.</li>
</ul>
<p>A cone is built by rotating a <strong>right triangle</strong> around one=
 of its catheti by <span class=3D"math-inline"><span class=3D"katex"><span =
class=3D"katex-mathml"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><=
semantics><mrow><mn>360</mn><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=C2=B0</mi></mrow><a=
nnotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">360\degree</annotation></semantics=
></math></span><span class=3D"katex-html" aria-hidden=3D"true"><span class=
=3D"base"><span class=3D"strut" style=3D"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0e=
m;"></span><span class=3D"mord">360=C2=B0</span></span></span></span></span=
>. Alternatively, you can rotate an <strong>isosceles triangle</strong> by =
<span class=3D"math-inline"><span class=3D"katex"><span class=3D"katex-math=
ml"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mn=
>180</mn><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=C2=B0</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=
=3D"application/x-tex">180\degree</annotation></semantics></math></span><sp=
an class=3D"katex-html" aria-hidden=3D"true"><span class=3D"base"><span cla=
ss=3D"strut" style=3D"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;"></span><span cl=
ass=3D"mord">180=C2=B0</span></span></span></span></span>. The result is a =
<strong>circular base</strong> connected to the vertex (or <strong>apex</st=
rong>) by the <strong>slant height</strong> of the cone.</p>
</div><div class=3D"textBlock textBlock__text-infoBox textBlock__text-infoB=
ox--primary"><p>=F0=9F=99=8B  Cones are the only elementary solids with a s=
ingle vertex!</p>
</div><div class=3D"textBlock"><p>If you "slice" a cone with a horizontal p=
lane. You obtain two shapes: a smaller cone, and a solid with two parallel =
<strong>circular bases</strong>: one is smaller than the other (the trivial=
 case in which the bases are identical is a cylinder). We call a truncated =
cone with parallel bases a <strong>frustum</strong>.</p>
<p>As the cone is the result of the rotation of a triangle, the frustum is =
the result of the rotation of a <a href=3D"https://www.calctool.org/math-an=
d-statistics/trapezoid" class=3D"js-link">trapezoid</a> (either right or is=
osceles).</p>
</div><div class=3D"textBlock textBlock__text-infoBox textBlock__text-infoB=
ox--secondary"><p>=F0=9F=94=8E  You can consider cones as "special" pyramid=
s obtained by increasing to infinity the number of sides of the base.</p>
</div></div><div class=3D"contentPart css-12zi0x1"><h2 id=3D"how-do-i-calcu=
late-the-volume-of-a-cone-what-is-the-formula-for-the-volume-of-a-cone">How=
 do I calculate the volume of a cone: what is the formula for the volume of=
 a cone?</h2>
<div class=3D"textBlock"><p>The formula for the <a href=3D"https://www.calc=
tool.org/conversion/volume-conversion" class=3D"js-link">volume</a> of a co=
ne has some similarities with the calculations of the volumes of other soli=
ds:</p>
</div><div class=3D"mathBlock"><span class=3D"katex-display"><span class=3D=
"katex"><span class=3D"katex-mathml"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/=
Math/MathML" display=3D"block"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo>=3D</mo><mfra=
